The South African Post Office plans to reduce its working hours and retrench employees in a bid to cut its wage bill, Chief Executive Officer Nomkhita Mona said. The state-owned company has been in a “downward spiral” since 2004, when it last posted a profit, and staff-related costs account for 68% of its total expenditure, Mona said in an interview with Johannesburg-based radio station SAfm on Friday. Read: Post Office contributes to R3bn licensing fraud loss The Post Office, mindful of South Africa’s sluggish economy and high unemployment, will prioritise reducing its working hours, before implementing a longer-term plan to cut staff, Mona said.